%I A395153 #18 Apr 23 2026 16:41:29
%S A395153 4,3,2,6,5,1,0,3,7,4,3,2,1,0,5,7,6,4,3,4,5,1,0,5,7,2,3,7,6,4,3,7,8,7,
%T A395153 4,6,5,2,1,7,6,6,5,7,2,7,6,8,12,2,7,8,7,2,1,7,8,5,4,6,5,2,12,5,6,9,8,
%U A395153 5,8,2,1,8,7,6,5,5,6,7,6,7,8
%N A395153 a(n) = number of iterations of f(n) = sigma(n) if sigma(n) < 2n (n deficient), else n / gpf(n) (where gpf(n) is the greatest prime factor), needed to reach a cycle, for n >= 2.
%C A395153 For n > 1, define f(n) as follows: if sigma(n) < 2*n (n is deficient), then f(n) = sigma(n); otherwise (n is abundant or perfect), f(n) = n / p, where p is the greatest prime factor of n (A006530). Iterating f eventually enters a cycle. Up to 10^9, only two cycles have been observed: C0 of length 3 (8 -> 15 -> 24 -> 8) and C1 of length 3 (512 -> 1023 -> 1536 -> 512). a(n) is the number of steps to first reach either cycle.
%C A395153 Empirical verification for all n up to 10^9 shows that the orbit always falls into one of these cycles; no other cycles have been found. Among all n <= 10^9, about 96.5122% enter the 3-cycle (8,15,24) and about 3.4878% enter the other 3-cycle (512,1023,1536) (based on a complete count).
%C A395153 Statistics for the first 100000 numbers (n = 2..100001): overall, 75.2008% are deficient and 24.7992% are nondeficient. Among those entering C0 (98.315% of the 100000), 74.8774% are deficient and 9.6985% are prime; among those entering C1 (1.685% of the 100000), 94.0653% are deficient and 3.3828% are prime. The average step count for C0 ranges from about 7.8 to 9.0, and for C1 from about 2.2 to 3.5, based on averages of consecutive 10000-term blocks in the first 100000 numbers.
%H A395153 Lu Zhuofan, <a href="/A395153/b395153.txt">Table of n, a(n) for n = 2..10000</a>
%e A395153 For n = 2: sigma(2) = 3 -> 4 -> 7 -> 8, and 8 is in cycle C0, so a(2) = 4.
%e A395153 For n = 8, a(8) = 0 because 8 is in cycle C0.
%e A395153 For n = 9: 9 -> 13 -> 14 -> 24, and 24 is in cycle C0, so a(9) = 3.
%e A395153 For n = 16: 16 -> 31 -> 32 -> 63 -> 104 -> 8, and 8 is in cycle C0, so a(16) = 5.
%e A395153 For n = 512, a(512) = 0 because 512 is in cycle C1.
%Y A395153 Cf. A000203 (sigma), A005100 (deficient numbers), A006530 (greatest prime factor), A394453 (iteration with smallest prime factor).
%K A395153 nonn,new
%O A395153 2,1
